const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "What is peaberry coffee?",
    a: "A peaberry is a naturally occurring genetic mutation where only one seed develops inside the coffee cherry instead of the usual two. The single seed grows into a small, round, dense bean rather than two flat-sided halves. Peaberries form in roughly 3 to 5% of any coffee harvest, are hand-sorted at the farm level, and are roasted and sold as a distinct product because they behave differently in the roaster and cup compared to standard flat beans."
  },
  {
    q: "Does peaberry coffee taste better?",
    a: "Many specialty roasters and cuppers believe peaberry coffee tastes different: not necessarily better in an absolute sense, but more concentrated and sometimes more clearly expressing the origin's character. The round bean roasts more evenly because heat reaches all surfaces consistently, unlike flat beans where one side faces the drum. Whether this produces a perceptibly better cup depends on the taster and the origin. Koa Coffee's Peaberry Kona has won multiple awards in competitive cupping, which is the most concrete evidence that peaberry can produce outstanding results when the underlying coffee is excellent."
  },
  {
    q: "Is peaberry coffee more expensive?",
    a: "Yes, peaberries are consistently more expensive than flat-bean grades from the same farm. The reasons are scarcity (only 3 to 5% of any harvest), hand-sorting labor (peaberries must be separated manually or by specialized equipment because their round shape passes through flat-bean sorters), and the roasting attention they require as a distinct product. For premium origins like Kona, the price premium for peaberry is significant: Koa Coffee's Peaberry starts at approximately $60 per bag versus $42 to $46 for their flat-bean grades."
  },
  {
    q: "How do you roast peaberry coffee differently?",
    a: "Peaberry beans are denser and rounder than flat beans, which means they absorb heat differently in the drum. Many roasters adjust their drum speed and heat application for peaberry lots to account for the round shape's tendency to move freely. Peaberries can also develop slightly faster than flat beans because of their smaller mass relative to surface area. In practice, experienced roasters who work with peaberry regularly treat them as a separate roast profile from the flat-bean lots from the same farm."
  },
  {
    q: "Where does the best peaberry coffee come from?",
    a: "Tanzania Peaberry is one of the most widely known peaberry designations, with an earthy, wine-fruited character distinctive to the Mount Kilimanjaro region. Kona Peaberry from Hawaii, particularly Koa Coffee's award-winning product, is considered one of the world's best expressions of what peaberry can be at the premium tier. Brazil, Kenya, Colombia, and many other origins also produce peaberry lots, though they are less commonly designated and sold as a distinct product compared to Tanzania and Kona."
  }
];

